{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17511176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17511176"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:38:50+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:38:50+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583548","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583548"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:18:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11712"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11712"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.43,0.06,0.05,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4327"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80572"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4327","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4327"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2022-04-10T11:22:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-03T14:37:44+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2022-10-06T20:50:16+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-24 11:06:05"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11712"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"738"}},"author":{"data":null},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65863"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1604"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5901"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7273"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37161"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65863"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80572","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80572"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 45-year-old woman has recently undergone successful laparoscopic sleeve gastrectomy. She presents to the General Practice clinic for routine follow-up and mentions that she has sent her surgeon a Facebook friend request. She is enthusiastic about her results and wants to share her experience on social media. The surgeon has an active social media presence and maintains a professional website describing their bariatric surgery practice.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate response for the surgeon?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Accept the request but limit access to personal posts","Ignore the request","Message the patient and tell her it is inappropriate to reach out on social media","Accept the request and suggest joining their private bariatric support group","Direct the patient to the practice\u0027s official social media page for updates"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario highlights the challenges of maintaining professional boundaries in the age of social media. The most appropriate action is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eignore the request\u003C/strong\u003E, as this maintains clear professional boundaries without potentially awkward confrontation. This approach aligns with professional guidelines that emphasise the importance of separating personal and professional relationships.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccepting the request but limiting access to personal posts\u003C/strong\u003E still crosses professional boundaries and may create confusion about the nature of the doctor-patient relationship. It also sets a precedent that could be difficult to maintain consistently with other patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMessaging the patient to tell her it is inappropriate\u003C/strong\u003E could be perceived as confrontational and may not be necessary. Ignoring the request is a more subtle way to maintain boundaries without causing potential discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAccepting the request and suggesting joining their private bariatric support group\u003C/strong\u003E inappropriately combines personal and professional relationships and could create privacy concerns for other patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirecting the patient to the practice\u0027s official social media page for updates\u003C/strong\u003E might seem like a professional approach, but it still indirectly encourages interaction on social media, which can blur professional boundaries. It is better to maintain a clear separation between personal and professional interactions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Australian Medical Association\u0027s social media guidelines emphasise maintaining professional standards online and establishing clear boundaries between personal and professional profiles. This helps prevent complications that can arise from power imbalances within doctor-patient relationships and maintains appropriate professional distance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Professional boundaries between doctors and patients must be maintained on social media platforms.","Doctors should not solicit or encourage patient testimonials about clinical care as per AHPRA guidelines.","Ignoring social media friend requests from patients helps maintain appropriate doctor-patient relationships."],"references":["Kind T. Professional guidelines for social media use: a starting point. AMA J Ethics. 2015 May 1;17(5):441-7. doi: 10.1001/journalofethics.2015.17.5.nlit1-1505. PMID: 25986088. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25986088/","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 21]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65863"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11712"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65863"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-21T16:52:24+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-21T16:56:05+10:30","number":7,"notes":"Revised the last distractor option to be more challenging and updated the explanation accordingly.","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-01-21T16:53:23+10:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plagiarism-report-4327-7.pdf?X-Amz-Content-Sha256=UNSIGNED-PAYLOAD\u0026X-Amz-Algorithm=AWS4-HMAC-SHA256\u0026X-Amz-Credential=DO00QAKVE68N83EBLT2J%2F20250929%2Fsyd1%2Fs3%2Faws4_request\u0026X-Amz-Date=20250929T214844Z\u0026X-Amz-SignedHeaders=host\u0026X-Amz-Expires=601200\u0026X-Amz-Signature=75162d05494a1b069584716023799e41af513136c334b0f48ab693e23a61e579"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4327"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80572"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9435"}},"generation":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisionGenerations","id":"13681"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synony